This is a first course in logic, focusing on propositional logic. The basic idea is to start with translations and semantics, then introduce proofs in a natural deduction framework, and finally to end the course by briefly discussing pragmatics and probability.

It was based on a ten-week course, and hence there are ten chapters, with the parts of the chapter corresponding to the lectures or section meetings. Each Chapter also comes with a list of practice problems. For many of the links below, there is a "Solution" link next to it, which is just like the page to its immediate left, but with the solutions filled in or indicated. If one is doing an online course, it might make sense to base the lecture on the version which does not contain the solutions and to do the problems together with the students as one goes along.

Please report typos and suggest improvements at [this google form](https://forms.gle/ebUDKCxVVUGr1uYs8) that allows anonymous submissions. Also feel free to just send an email to walsh at ucla.edu. If you are an instructor and would like copies of homeworks and exams, feel free to email.

